Some 61 percent are concerned about facing "dangerously long" waits, a study revealed. And two-thirds do not think they would be seen quickly in A&E if they needed emergency care.  It comes amid reports of ambulances taking hours to arrive, and the NHS struggling with widespread staffing gaps. The survey of more than 1,000 British adults, carried out by Ipsos, also found the public was concerned about long waiting lists for treatment. 